I think this practicum is hard because it is a chance to see if a topic - a research question - has legs. Writing about others' ideas is (relatively) easy for me; adding my own voice is altogether different.

I think this process is hard because

&nbsp;

I'm starting routines this summer around reading, writing and learning. I am following the <a href="http://codeyear.com">Code Year</a> track at the open, teach-yourself programming website the Code Academy, built upon the premise one can learn to code in one-week lessons over one year. <img id="il_fi" style="padding-right: 8px; padding-top: 8px; padding-bottom: 8px;" src="http://static.tumblr.com/shwzhon/27Ulppwjo/code_academy_logo__transparent_.png" alt="" width="344" height="321" />

Code Academy is free. The reasons for this include the possibility of an exponential return on investment for Code Academy's founders, employees and investors, the difficulty of valuing fast-growing companies, and not grasping just how far and fast open, online learning may grow. It occurred to me Code Academy is undervalued by a lot - it is free for now - therefore it's undervalued by at least an ∞ amount. Now is a good time for educational technology and open, free resources. Things won't be this way forever.

&nbsp;

Last year, while I took <em>The Intellectual History of Educational Psychology</em> (CEP 911) and became interested in cognitive psychology,<em> </em>I signed up for the <a href="http://www.cogsci.msu.edu/contact.html" target="_blank">cognitive science listserv </a>(at MSU). Also last year, I signed up to receive the <a href="http://www.matt-koehler.com/tpack/tpack-newsletters/" target="_blank">TPACK newsletter</a>.

Earlier this year, I signed up for the <a href="https://mailman.ucsd.edu/mailman/listinfo/xmca-l" target="_blank">listserv associated with the <em>Mind, Culture, and Activity</em> journal</a>. Finally, through special interest groups (SIGs) associated with the AERA and SITE conferences, I was automatically signed up for their respective mailing lists or listservs.

While social media is increasingly important for creating and consuming news, and communicating, these mailing lists, newsletters, and listservs have been really important to me. This is especially true of the TPACK newsletters, but also the mailing lists and listservs associated with conferences, which provided information on related conferences, opportunities for service and presentations and publications, and news.

I think the best places to find mailing lists, newsletters, and listservs is in the academic or professional communities in which we are already engaged -- and to ask advisors and colleagues to recommend where to start.

&nbsp;

